<Transcription-Unit ID='ECOLI:TU0-4703' orgid='ECOLI' frameid='TU0-4703' detail='full'><replicon><Genetic-Element resource='getxml?ECOLI:COLI-K12' orgid='ECOLI' frameid='COLI-K12'/></replicon>
<common-name datatype='string'>lacZYA</common-name>
<comment datatype='string'>The &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon is controlled by four promoters, P1, which is the principal promoter, P2, and P3 and P4, the weaker promoters [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1649816&quot;&gt;Xiong91&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1650341&quot;&gt;Eschenlauer91&lt;/a&gt;]. Transcription of this operon is both negatively and positively regulated. Negative regulation occurs when the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; repressor (LacI) binds to the operator, preventing transcription by RNA polymerase [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6259624&quot;&gt;Schmitz81&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;]. Positive regulation is mediated by the cAMP receptor protein, CRP (also referred to as the catabolite activator protein, CAP)  [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1649816&quot;&gt;Xiong91&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1650341&quot;&gt;Eschenlauer91&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15385551&quot;&gt;Liu04a&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
In the presence of glucose, &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon expression is not needed and a control mechanism known as catabolite repression occurs. This refers to the ability of glucose to inhibit expression of the operon. As cellular cAMP levels drop in response to glucose uptake, CRP is not activated and operon expression is inhibited. Under this mechanism, &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; genes are only expressed if lactose is present and glucose is absent.  
&lt;p&gt;
In the absence of glucose, the levels of cAMP increase and this metabolite binds to CRP. CRP becomes active and it binds to DNA near the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; promoter, facilitating transcription [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/6259624&quot;&gt;Schmitz81&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;].  Synthesis of the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon proteins is induced when &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt; is grown on lactose in the absence of glucose. CRP is the principal activator of the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon. CRP interacts with RNA polymerase and stimulates transcription of lacZp1 by increasing the binding of the RNA polymerase and the open complex stabilization [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/12881519&quot;&gt;Liu03&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8735277&quot;&gt;Savery96&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/9737918&quot;&gt;Noel98&lt;/a&gt;].  In the same way, CRP completely overlaps lacZp2 and lacZp3, avoiding RNA polymerase binding and preventing transcription of these promoters [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1650341&quot;&gt;Eschenlauer91&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/1649816&quot;&gt;Xiong91&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
On the other hand, in the absence of allolactose, the LacI repressor represses the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950160&quot;&gt;Lewis05a&lt;/a&gt;]. In this repression system, LacI binds to two operators centered at positions 10 bp (O1) and -82 bp (O3), and formation of the repressor loop is critical [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8984648&quot;&gt;Fried96&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/8984647&quot;&gt;Perros96&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/14725772&quot;&gt;Balaeff04&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;]. Expression of p1 is also stimulated when LacI binds to O1 [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
Induction occurs when the physiological inducer, allolactose, binds to the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; repressor, preventing it from binding to the operator [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15950160&quot;&gt;Lewis05a&lt;/a&gt;]. Nonphysiological analogs, such as thiogalactosides, can function as inducers too. Activation of the &lt;i&gt;lac&lt;/i&gt; operon can also be partly increased by CRP when it overlaps the O1 site, acting as an antirepressor [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/3315229&quot;&gt;Straney87&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2166165&quot;&gt;Hudson90&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
The expression of the lac operon is differently regulated in many strains of &lt;i&gt;E. coli&lt;/i&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31719176&quot;&gt;Phillips19&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
